SIMPLE: officious
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Officious
<hw>Of*fi"cious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>officiosus</ets>: cf. F. <ets>officieux</ets>. See
<er>Office</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Pertaining to, or being in
accordance with, duty.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If there were any lie in the case, it could be no more than an
<qex>officious</qex> and venial one.</q> <rj><qau>Note on Gen. xxvii.
(Douay version).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Disposed to serve; kind; obliging.</def>
<mark>[Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Yet not to earth are those bright luminaries⟦br⟧
<qex>Officious</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They were tolerably well bred, very <qex>officious</qex>, humane,
and hospitable.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Importunately interposing services; intermeddling in
affairs in which one has no concern; meddlesome.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You are too <qex>officious</qex>⟦br⟧
In her behalf that scorns your services.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Impertinent; meddling. See
<er>Impertinent</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Of*fi"cious*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Of*fi"cious*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 999 --></p>

<p><ent>Offing</ent>⟦br⟧
